<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,694,1187]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,348,874,899]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">Pollen hosts.</emphasis>
Probably oligolectic on 
<taxonomicName box="[620,724,874,899]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
with a distinct preference for 
<taxonomicName box="[1057,1192,874,899]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="tribe" tribe="Hedysareae">Hedysareae</taxonomicName>
: all 
<number box="[1236,1264,874,899]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" value="15.0">15</number>
pollen loads (
<number box="[1422,1436,875,899]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" value="3.0">3</number>
localities, 
<number box="[268,282,911,935]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" value="1.0">1</number>
country) analyzed so far exclusively consisted of 
<taxonomicName box="[859,963,910,935]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
pollen; among these, 
<number box="[1218,1246,911,935]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" value="13.0">13</number>
loads as well as one brood cell only contained 
<taxonomicName box="[491,622,946,971]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="tribe" tribe="Hedysareae">Hedysareae</taxonomicName>
pollen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,694,1187]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,392,982,1007]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">Nesting biology.</emphasis>
One brood cell was found about 
<quantity box="[784,832,982,1007]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" unit="cm" value="5.0">5cm</quantity>
deep in a preexisting insect burrow in rather loamy ground (C. Praz and C. Sedivy, personal communication; 
<figureCitation box="[798,865,1018,1043]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1880,1902]" captionTargetBox="[187,1411,337,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[187,1411,337,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1: Hoplitis haplophylli, clypeus of female. 2: Hoplitis haplophylli, sterna 3 – 6 of male. 3: Hoplitis haplophylli, terga 4 – 7 of male. 4: Hoplitis haplophylli, antenna of male. 5: Hoplitis taenioceras, antenna of male. 6: Hoplitis heinrichi: tarsus of middle leg. 7: Hoplitis heinrichi: last antennal segment of male. 8: Hoplitis illustris: last antennal segment of male. 9: Hoplitis heinrichi: brood cell in preexisting insect burrow in the ground, which is entirely constructed from chewed leaves; below the cell, a partition of chewed leaves has been built, separating the cell from the lower part of the burrow." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230854/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">
Fig. 
<number box="[849,865,1019,1043]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). The urn-shaped cell, which had a length of about 
<quantity box="[151,223,1055,1079]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" unit="mm" value="11.0">11mm</quantity>
, consisted entirely of chewed green leaves, without admixture of sand or pebbles. However, the cell was over much of its length directly attached to the walls of the insect burrow so that it could not be removed from the burrow without damaging it. About 
<quantity box="[557,614,1127,1151]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" unit="mm" value="1.0">1mm</quantity>
below the cell, a partition of chewed leaves was built, separating the cell from the lower part of the burrow.
</paragraph>
